Eh,Noel, dobar dan i dobro nan doša.
Prije nego krenemo s razgovoron, reči nan eh ča smo upravo slušali.
Eh, pjesma nosi naziv # "Šenice su klasale".

Good day to you, uh, our dear [listeners] and welcome to Čakaviana.
Today uh we will host Noel Šuran.
Immediately uh after we hear a uh musical number of his.
And welcome back uh my guest uh on Čakaviana today uh is a cultural anthropologist uh artist and musician from Lindar, Noel Šuran.
Uh Noel, good day and welcome.
Before we start with the conversation, tell us uh what we just listened to.
Uh, the song bears the title "The wheat has formed ears"
So, we must say that the reason uh for your appearance is the recent promotion of this very project, "All by myself".
Uh, that is to say you recorded yourself singing uh old traditional melodies from our region "on thin and fat" [in two-part harmony].
Uh, to begin with uh how and why in general did you come to/ to this idea?
Uh, describe to us a little how this process itself of creating your audio recordings looks.
Good day to all the listeners.
Yes, this is a song that is neglected, I think it's neglected, it's rarely heard.
I uh heard it from a traditional singer who sang it with her brother-in-law.
And then in this project  "All by myself" I put it on a CD and made it so that others can learn it.
Well, the idea dawned on me ah all by myself/
Today there's a problem of people getting together and somehow that social moment, which there used to be a lot of, as we would say/
People got together much more and/ and/ spontaneously/ and needed to do some work with one another and so, and then they normally also would sing.

Today you can hm sing if there is some occasion, if there is some kind of festival or meeting, so only if people somehow arrange this and go, but otherwise, it's like this, if you want to sing somewhere uh for your own enjoyment, you can, but only by yourself.
And I somehow came up with the idea that one should record these songs uh that are simpler, traditional ones, so that more people could learn them.
Since uh that method of learning by ear and by the principle of imitation is traditional.
It's normal, that's one old way.
So, in my fundamental work I separated the thin [high] from the fat [low] voice.
And you have an example when you hear it, both the thin [high] and fat [low] together, how it sounds.
And then, whoever may want to learn, let's say, the thin [high] voice, meaning the second part, just listens to the recording where the thin voice is sung.
And then you simply get it into your ear, and then you master that part.
Here it's not that you have a score for the first voice, a score for the second voice, as children and young people were taught in this manner up to now.
So, uh, it was turned into sheet music, into a first and second part for the voice, and then you would perform this from the printed music.
And now I have, according to that principle of imitation, as it once was and as the most important contribution has been made
Uh, so you try to imi/ in the first phase to imitate as closely as possible, to copy the/ the/ the voice that you hear.
Uh, first of all, I collected recordings in the field.
I didn't collect this in one year but rather over a number of years.
So here, let's say, one example, one song, uh, "Hey, girl/", uh "Hey girl, flower of youth" was sung by an old [female] singer who lived here in Pula, but was otherwise a native of the Cere area.
And she was even, uh, a member, uh, during the time of the War of National Liberation [WWII], that is, in/ in the amateur troupe "Otokar Keršovani".
She was both an actress and a singer.
And in the 40s she uh performed with oth/ other singers and players, and that was really the beginning of cultural-artistic activity uh in Istria.
And I met her here in Pula when I lived [here].
Uh and from her I learned a number of songs, with her I also began to sing a lot of songs, too.
And that fascinated me, let's say, when I would come to her place.
She lived there on Kvarner Street.
She lived alone, she was a widow when I knew her.
She was around 80 years old, 83 or 84.
And she had a cassette tape player.
And then she would start the cassette tape player
And it would begin to sing.
She had recorded the fat [low] voice herself.
And when it would start to sing then she would accompany it on the thin [high] part.
And she would sing with the cassette tape player.
And it fascinated me so that/ that I uh this/ and that project afterwards that would be that "All by myself" in some way, uh, and that/

that story which from that time kept bugging me that it was necessary, since it's the easiest way to perform some song that you haven't sung or that is in your head while you teach someone to sing the second voice for you.
Then you automatically have the first voice, you sing it, and then you add the thin [high] voice and then you have a complete song.
